8:
And my time is valuable, see... Worth 
one or two lives, even.
10: No! Please! Just don't kill anyone!
12: Then you'd better give me what I want.
13:
But if you take all our food, that'd be 
the same as killing us! Have mercy, 
sir! At least leave enough for the 
women and children.
15:
Oh, don't you worry about that. We'll 
be collecting your belles and your 
brats, along with the grub.
17:
Still stalling, eh?
Hey, fellas! What do you think my rate 
should be? One life a minute?
18:
A-all right! I'll take you to the 
storehouses!
23: It's darker than the inside of a camel...
36: Sink into the depths... Sand Falchion!
42: Adil! Your plan was a success!
43:
My family's safe again! How can we 
ever thank you?
45:
Let me use this town as a pit stop 
between hunting trips. That'll be more 
than enough.
47: What if we just built you a house?
49:
That's brilliant! No bandits'll be able to 
touch us when Adil's around!
52:
No. I wouldn't stay in it long enough 
to justify the cost.
54:
...Then, please, at least take this. It's 
food and water.
57:
Your kind words are reward enough. 
Now, if you'll excuse me.
60:
And there he goes... Empty-handed 
again…
66:
Travelers? What brings you all the 
way out here?
68:
We saw a bunch of dust go up and 
got kind of worried but…
70: Oh. Well, everyone's fine now. Thanks.
72:
...Though now that you're here, there's
a favor I'd like to ask of you.
74:
Could you deliver these gifts and a 
message? You see, there's this man, 
and he acts pretty reserved around 
us, but we—
77:
Will you not tell us the story from the 
beginning?
93: We've got a delivery for you!
102:
These are gifts of gratitude, not tokens
to buy forgiveness.
103:
They will never forget that they 
abandoned your village in its time of 
need... It is a burden they are prepared 
to shoulder for the rest of their lives.
109:
I-I mean... I can't believe they told you
all that…
118:
This place is a wasteland. Even the 
royals don't send their patrols out 
here. Inhabitants are always being 
forced to choose between their own 
lives or the lives of their neighbors.
120:
One day, there was a famine. The 
people who gave me these gifts chose 
to survive, and my own village was left 
to die.
122:
In a way, they're carrying around the 
lives of my friends and family. 
I couldn't let bandits get to them—
that's all.
126: Will you go on fighting alone?
130:
I don't want to lose anything ever 
again.
133: Then will you not come with us?
134:
We know of a place where neighbors 
extend their hands not to take from, 
but to aid one another.
136:
You will find comrades there, willing 
to fight alongside you.
139:
Heh. Sounds like you're trying to sell 
me on a dream.
140:
But your eyes say it all. You're dead 
serious, aren't you?
149:
Yeah, I'll bite. Who better to make 
miracles happen than a mysterious 
boy and a talking animal?
